<h2>Content design</h2>
<p>Plan the words and pictures together. Each content block should communicate one primary concept or action, and every part of the page should help people understand or use the information.</p>

<h3>Writing content</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Write for the identified audience and the task they need to complete.</li>
  <li>Use short sentences.</li>
  <li>Communicate one idea per sentence.</li>
  <li>Begin new ideas on a new line or in a new paragraph.</li>
  <li>Use common words.</li>
  <li>Explain difficult words immediately.</li>
  <li>Use active voice.</li>
  <li>Avoid jargon, idioms and unexplained acronyms.</li>
  <li>Use clear, descriptive link labels that make sense out of context.</li>
  <li>Keep the content concise.</li>
  <li>Test the content with people who use Easy Read.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Difficult words and definitions</h3>
<p>Use a common word when it keeps the meaning accurate. When a difficult or specialist word is necessary, make it bold the first time and explain it immediately in the next sentence. Use the same term consistently after defining it.</p>
<p>Do not make people follow a link or open a separate glossary to understand an essential instruction.</p>

<h3>Images and illustrations</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Choose illustrations when a simplified scene makes the concept clearer. Choose photographs when recognising a real person, place, object or action matters.</li>
  <li>Show one concept per image and keep the visual treatment consistent across the page.</li>
  <li>Limit unnecessary background detail and avoid text embedded in an image.</li>
  <li>Use respectful representation and review imagery for cultural safety.</li>
  <li>Give informative images meaningful alternative text that describes the information they add.</li>
  <li>Only use the explicit <code>decorative</code> option when an image adds no information.</li>
  <li>Test whether the intended audience understands each image and its relationship to the text.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Generated images</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Require human review before publishing.</li>
  <li>Check for bias, stereotypes and harmful representation.</li>
  <li>Check factual and visual accuracy, including hands, objects, labels and sequences.</li>
  <li>Do not use generated imagery for unverified safety-critical instructions.</li>
  <li>Confirm licensing and organisational policy requirements.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Read aloud</h2>
<p>Read Aloud is an optional platform enhancement. Do not add a vendor-specific JavaScript implementation to the design system.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Place the Listen control near the beginning of the Easy Read content.</li>
  <li>Ensure the reading order follows the DOM.</li>
  <li>Test keyboard access.</li>
  <li>Test pause, stop and speed controls where provided.</li>
  <li>Test word or sentence highlighting where provided.</li>
  <li>Do not treat Read Aloud as a replacement for semantic HTML or screen-reader testing.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Downloadable formats</h2>
<p>Accessible HTML is the primary version. Supply an accessible PDF or Word version when user needs require it. EPUB can be useful for long-form or collected content.</p>
<p>Accessible EPUBs should conform to EPUB Accessibility 1.1 and preferably WCAG 2.2 AA. Label every file with its format, size and updated date.</p>
<div class="nsw-callout">
  <div class="nsw-callout__content">
    <p class="nsw-h4">Static download example</p>
    <p><a href="#">Download all transport Easy Read articles (EPUB, 3.1 MB, updated 20 July 2026)</a></p>
  </div>
</div>
<p>The example represents a pre-generated file. Creation, accessibility checks and versioning belong in the CMS or build system. Do not generate a “download all” bundle in the browser.</p>

<h2>Testing and review</h2>
<p>Use a multi-stage review: content self-review, peer review, accessibility review and usability testing. Include people with intellectual disability and other people from the identified audience. Pay them for their expertise and allow enough time and support for meaningful participation.</p>
<p>Test the complete experience, not isolated sentences. Check comprehension, image meaning, navigation, links, downloads and any Listen control.</p>

<h2>Accessibility requirements</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Use semantic headings in a logical hierarchy. Content-block titles default to H2 and only allow H3 as a controlled alternative.</li>
  <li>Provide meaningful alternative text for every informative image and explicitly mark decorative images.</li>
  <li>Keep the reading and focus order consistent with the visual order.</li>
  <li>Use descriptive links and visible keyboard focus.</li>
  <li>Support keyboard-only use, screen readers and text resizing to 200%.</li>
  <li>Verify reflow at a 320 CSS pixel viewport and at 400% browser zoom.</li>
  <li>Test light, dark and inverted themes without relying on colour alone.</li>
  <li>Keep accessible HTML as the primary format even when documents or Read Aloud are available.</li>
</ul>
